 into its early medieval context and explaining Hincmar's sometimes-dubious methods of argument.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDivorce (Canon law). 4aMedieval Sources 2017. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aCarolingian Renaissance.  aDe divortio.  aFrankish Europe.  aHincmar of Rheims.  aLothar II.  aTheutberga.  aWaldrada.  abishops.  adivorce.  aearly medieval attitudes.  akingship.  amarriage.  apolitical wrangling.  apolitics.  asociety.  asterility.  asuccession.1 aStone, Rachel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStone, Rachel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWest, Charles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWest, Charles, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packagez978311128281740uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978178499743440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781784997434423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781784997434/original  a978-3-11-128281-7  Manchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packageb2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles